    body:`<p>The floating dock at Riverside Park's Pier 1 is a quiet spot on most Saturday mornings — a narrow walkway that juts over the Hudson just south of 72nd Street, used mostly by dog walkers, joggers cutting through, and the occasional early riser who wants to stand over the water before the city catches up. The dock boards get slick when the temperature drops near freezing, particularly after rain. A Parks Department maintenance log reviewed by the Good Report shows the section had been flagged for resurfacing in February; the work had not yet been completed.</p>
<p>At approximately 9:50 a.m. on Saturday, Margaret Calloway, 74, a retired librarian who lives nearby and walks the pier several mornings a week, stepped onto one of those boards. Her foot slid. She went into the Hudson.</p>
<p>Liam Petry was on the dock about thirty feet away, standing with a friend. He heard the sound of her hitting the water and turned before most of the handful of other bystanders had registered what happened. By the time they did, Petry — 17, a junior at a Manhattan high school — had already taken off his jacket and gone in after her.</p>
<p>"He was just gone," said his friend, who asked not to be named. "I looked over and he was already in the water. I don't think I'll ever fully understand how fast that was."</p>
<div class="pull-quote">"The cold takes your breath away immediately. I just tried to stay focused on getting to her."</div>
<p>The water temperature in the Hudson at that stretch of Riverside Park on Saturday morning was 41 degrees, according to FDNY Harbor Unit records. The current near the pier runs at roughly two to three knots. Calloway, who does not swim strongly, had gone under once before surfacing and was struggling to stay up when Petry reached her — approximately twenty feet from where she had gone in.</p>
<p>"The cold takes your breath away immediately," Petry said in a brief phone interview Saturday evening. "I just tried to stay focused on getting to her and not thinking about anything else."</p>
<p>He got to Calloway, positioned himself behind her, and kept her head above water. He held her there, treading in 41-degree current, until two bystanders on the dock lowered a life ring from the pier's safety equipment. Petry got it around Calloway, and both were pulled toward the dock. FDNY Harbor Unit Boat 1 arrived within five minutes of a 911 call placed by a bystander during the rescue.</p>
<p>Calloway was transported to NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital, where she was treated for hypothermia and a bruised shoulder. She was listed in stable condition Saturday afternoon. Her son, reached by phone, said she had been asking about the teenager since she was admitted.</p>
<p>"She wants to thank him," he said. "She said she remembers looking up and seeing him in the water next to her and just feeling like she was going to be okay."</p>
<p>Petry was assessed by EMS at the scene and released. He declined transport to the hospital. He said he was fine, that he had warmed up, and that he hoped Mrs. Calloway recovered quickly.</p>
<p>FDNY Harbor Unit Lt. Andre Simmons said Petry's immediate entry was the decisive factor. "At 41 degrees, you have a limited window," Simmons said. "He didn't wait to see if someone else would go in. He went. That made the difference."</p>
<p>The Parks Department confirmed the dock section has been closed pending inspection and that the deferred resurfacing work will be completed before it reopens.</p>
<p>Petry said he had not thought much about what he did. "It was a person in the water," he said. "I was right there."</p>`,
